WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:36.040 --> 00:00:41.300
What each of us looks for in our significant personal relationships will differ from person to person.

00:00:42.100 --> 00:00:48.520
If we value reflection, personal growth, and independent thought, we'll want our relationships to support those things.

00:00:49.060 --> 00:00:55.420
Games and creative pursuits might be important features, giving us an outlet for the playful, inventive parts of our nature.

00:00:56.020 --> 00:01:02.340
Something we might consider a relationship essential is the ability to just relax and be our authentic selves.

00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:09.320
We might also expect a healthy sense of security, so there's no fear that an innocent slip could land us in trouble,

00:01:09.500 --> 00:01:12.840
or that accidents and misunderstandings will get blown out of scale

00:01:13.929 --> 00:01:17.039
Whatever positive, affirming features you look for in a relationship,

00:01:17.710 --> 00:01:22.710
you can forget all about them when malignant narcissists manoeuvre themselves into your life.

00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:29.860
Personal growth, independent thought, creativity, and authenticity will all get shoved into storage,

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:32.980
leaving you in a rigid, stagnant environment.

00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:39.280
Security will evaporate as you begin to realise one wrong step could do you serious damage.

00:01:40.119 --> 00:01:44.968
To malignant narcissists, your value begins and ends with your ability to serve them.

00:01:45.820 --> 00:01:49.680
Dismissing your needs is just the start: soon the mind games begin.

00:01:50.340 --> 00:01:55.820
Like stepping into an Escher print, you'll find yourself completely disorientated by the impossible angles

00:01:55.940 --> 00:02:00.700
of the narcissist's world, where the only predictable feature is unpredictability.

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:04.640
Not only is there no telling where you'll end up when you go through a door,

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:07.200
there's no telling what laws will apply when you get there.

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:11.160
Down might now mean up or sideways.

00:02:11.760 --> 00:02:16.140
With each vertigo-inducing flip your brain tries to find some underlying order,

00:02:16.820 --> 00:02:20.720
and when you think you might have found it the ground falls from under you

00:02:21.700 --> 00:02:24.900
Narcissists use a range of mind games to knock targets off balance,

00:02:25.040 --> 00:02:29.660
including love-bombing, gaslighting, and various forms of emotional blackmail.

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:37.200
I want to explore a particularly poisonous mind game called the double bind, which puts people in no-win situations.

00:02:38.180 --> 00:02:42.980
I'll be looking at examples of it in action and some different ways of dealing with it.

00:02:48.090 --> 00:02:54.349
A no-win manipulation could be defined as the act of putting targets in situations where all actions lead to a negative outcome.

00:02:54.810 --> 00:03:02.569
An example would be what's called a Kafka trap: in Kafka traps targets are accused typically of some psychological flaw.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:08.089
When they deny the accusation, their denial is taken as evidence that the accusation is true.

00:03:08.430 --> 00:03:12.739
The possibility that the accusation is false is invalidly excluded.

00:03:13.739 --> 00:03:17.779
Targets of Kafka traps are only presented with losing options by their accuser.

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:24.709
In fact, in many cases, targets do have positive options; one is to simply ignore their accusers.

00:03:25.079 --> 00:03:28.909
Another is to expose and mock this fallacious manipulation.

00:03:29.460 --> 00:03:32.760
With double binds, these options aren't available.

00:03:33.260 --> 00:03:36.800
A double bind is a very specific kind of no-win manipulation

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:41.260
in which targets are presented with conflicting messages, each of which and negates the other.

00:03:41.840 --> 00:03:45.260
In effect, they're told "do X" and "don't do X".

00:03:45.860 --> 00:03:50.380
When targets are playful, they might be criticised for never taking anything seriously.

00:03:50.380 --> 00:03:54.540
Then, when they're serious, they're told to stop being a drag and lighten up.

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:57.700
The double message is: "be serious and don't be serious".

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:01.400
Whatever the target chooses, the abuser responds with the other.

00:04:02.099 --> 00:04:08.569
Double binds occur in relationships where targets feel compelled to figure out what the manipulator wants and provide it.

00:04:08.849 --> 00:04:13.548
They feel unable to ignore the dilemma presented to them, which is what binds them in.

00:04:14.010 --> 00:04:20.720
They often feel unable to point out the injustice of the dilemma because criticism leads to more negative consequences.

00:04:21.299 --> 00:04:24.709
And, they're unable to consult the manipulator to help find a way out.

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:28.860
Double binds can be extremely destructive, psychologically.

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:34.300
Targets of narcissists can tie themselves in knots trying to work out what the narcissist wants.

00:04:34.620 --> 00:04:37.880
But all the narcissist actually wants is to make the target fail.

00:04:38.460 --> 00:04:43.280
Through repeated experiences of failure, targets can end up in a state of learned helplessness

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:46.440
where they feel unable to control or change a situation.

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:52.420
Making decisions can become increasingly difficult as targets start habitually questioning their own judgment.

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:57.040
As they become more passive and compliant, the narcissist takes control.

00:05:03.020 --> 00:05:09.700
